<br>
<br>
<DIV class="poemtitle">In the Carriage Window</DIV><br>
<TABLE><TR><TD>
<br /> 
She stares past me, constant against the blur,<br /> 
faintly supercilious; perhaps she knows<br /> 
that from now on her beauty will always colour<br /> 
this fragile landscape through which she ghosts,<br /> 
its sparse march of telegraph posts,<br /> 
its vanishing hedgerows,<br /> 
its fleeing meadows.	<br /> 
<br /> 
Does this cool spirit care for the country?<br /> 
She is free of its concerns, even though<br /> 
for me her image seems to guarantee<br /> 
its value, as if a rare watermark,<br /> 
brighter against the lowering dark,<br /> 
which touches a hedgerow,<br /> 
kisses a meadow.<br /> 

<br><br>

<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('payne')">by Stephen Payne</a></td></tr></table><br><br>
<br>
  <img src="images/carriage_window.jpg"><br>
